author: @muhammadabdullahdilshad8509
text: Notes ---------------------->>>>>>  #only be executed only if the condition is true if True:     print('Conditional Was true')  #using variables in the Conditionals language = 'python' if language == 'python': #Double Equal is Equality     print("The langauge is Python") else:     print("No Match") #Runs when the codnition is not True   #We can also use the elif for Multiple ifs language = 'java' if language == 'python': #Double Equal is Equality     print("The langauge is Python") elif language =='java':     print("Language is Java") else:     print("No Match") #Runs when the codnition is not True   # Boolean Operations  # and # or # not  #######  AND ######## # returns the true if all the Condiitons are ture user = 'Admin' logged_in = False if user == 'Admin' and logged_in:     print("Admin Page") else:     print("bad Creds")  ######### OR ########## # Retuens true if only one of the condition is true  user = 'Admin' logged_in = False if user == 'Admin' or  logged_in:     print("Admin Page") else:     print("bad Creds")  ######## NOT ###########  user = 'Admin' logged_in = False if user == 'Admin' and not logged_in:     print("Admin Page") else:     print("bad Creds")  a=[1,2,3] b=[1,2,3] print(a is b) #Because both of these lists are different so retuns false why ? print(id(a)) print(id(b)) print(a==b) ## But the equality retuns true    # What makes the condition actually False #False Values:     # False     # None     # Zero of any numeric type     # Any empty sequence. For example, '', (), [].     # Any empty mapping. For example, {}.  random = 50 if random:     print('Evaluated to True') else:     print('Evaluated to False')
